text: I still don't understand why people are hating this movie so much.  I mean, I know that it has flaws, like those big action sequences, but it looks like Agent 47 doesn't actively go into gunfights, rather he is forced, and although it was rare in the games, it did happen. Also, I don't think it's gonna be very fun to watch 2 hours of 47 waiting around for the guards to leave in order to poison the target's food. So there has to be some action, but it has to be forcefully brought upon 47. In addition to that, they need to make the stealthy parts of the movie more fun by adding more movement and tension, rather than having 47 be in a closet ready to KO an unsuspecting person.  Also the action sequences could be a few in the movie which were put into the trailer in order to attract a wider audience, this is common in trailers, they misrepresent the movie.  By the way, at 1:04 it looks like he'll be using disguises, stealth and subterfuge. So indeed, I don't think this movie will have 47 enter a room and shoot his way through it.  Another problem is that part of the plot seems a bit cliche, with the whole "One of your relatives (very often your parents) was very important somehow and now we need you because of reasons."  So, in summary, I feel like this movie could be great, all they need to do is correctly explain and "force" the actions sequences (which I feel they will since it looks like they're sticking to the games), make the action sequences few. And correctly execute the plot and they're done.   P.S. I think Rupert Friend will be better than Timothy Olyphant. He looks like he'll nail the character down. And also, Rupert looks more like 47 than Olyphant.

text: There's so much about this trailer that already shows it'll suck. First of all, they got the entire look of 47 wrong. He doesn't just have a shaved head in the games, he's BALD! He doesn't have a single hair on his entire head, but in this they just shaved the actor's skull. They also screwed up the barcode on the back of his head. Next, why did the investigator even bring a sniper rifle into the room? Was he trying to intimidate 47 with it? Why would anyone be worried, I doubt it's okay to just shoot someone while interrogating them. Besides, a simple pistol or knife would have done the job. The rest is just a regular Hollywood action movie explosion fest. I swear if they try to recycle the basic plot of the last movie and Absolution I swear I will flip out. We don't need the Agency to be hunting him AGAIN. It wasn't good the last two times they did it either and it won't be good now. The cheesy lines and gun play in this trailer also kind of makes me think they'll have 47 just another boring, cliched action hero.

text: Why bother to use the name HITMAN? Oh, because it's a cash-cow....  Don't expect this piece of generic hollywood, copypasta have any resemblence to Hitman. The Hitman series have always (except for Hitman: Absolute Abomination) had a great amount of depth, a serious tone to it. From the atmosphere, to the level design, to the amazing soundtrack by Jesper Kyd.  Agent 47 does not look like a little kid cracking childish jokes. Agent 47 has a rather dark humor. Agent 47 does not do any fancy moves that are supposed to look ''cool'' (which it does not, it just look very cheesy and pathetic and just shows that this is a generic production which we all have seen before). He is more similar to an older, wiser man, with a dark, cold voice, and everything he is very delibirate and precise.   A proper Hitman movie would be a 2,30h long thriller. Maybe starting off with the psycological horror that is apparent in his escape from the Asylum, dead bodies all over, swat teams moving in accompanied by ''Jespers Kyd - Swat team''.  This movie is no more than casual, generic, cheap rubbish with no depth at all.

text: I was about to drop my food when I heard about this trailer. Now I am sorry for seeing it. A Hitman movie can have some action but he normally takes out his victims in a very calculated manner. The "You brought me my gun" scene is absolutely retarded, even if he is unnaturally fast. Isn't a beautifully scripted hit like "Oceans 11" more suitable for realism AND entertainment? That is what makes the game great: a symphony of actions all timely constructed for the ultimate end game. "BUM!, CARS! BOOBS!" is getting old now. Furthermore 47's story is quite amazing and filled with emotion even though he seems to lack any. Exploring his twisted mind and exceptional relationships was the way to go. First movie: bad, this one: worse.

Yet there he is in the interrogation room, telling them "I am 47". REALLY?! The Agents are bred to kill, are bound to secrecy and are trained to resist torture to complement that. text: No Olyphant, no film. Plus I hate Olyphant anyway... he only did the first Hitman because he wanted some money to buy a new car. Whether he said that as a joke or not is irrelevant, the point is, is that he had no intention and no interest in doing another afterwards and for that, he is a dick.  Also I completely agree and I find it super annoying when Hollywood gets their paws into any adaption of a game or book. Thing is... action sells and dumb people (the majority of cinema goers) will be quite content with a shitty back story and a lack of cohesion. Transformers 2 onwards is a perfect example of this. With this film however, as Mickey has said, is simply far too action hero and obviously this is just for the "oooooh" "aahhhh" effect, because few people want to see a man sneaking around trying to avoid being seen. In any case, even if more people did like a better story and a closer following with his profession and tie-ins to the game, the movie studio doesn't care and will ruin every franchise it gets its hands on because they will always choose the option where the biggest money is. Imagine a movie studio who willingly dropped millions for a better story? Haha, yeah right.  This is going to be a colossal flop. No amount of special effects and super man stunts can save this film... unless of course you're an idiot and just like things that go bang, da-da-da-da-da-da-da and crack, with little reason for doing so.  Oh, and bravo to the clowns who picked this guy to replace Timothy... you truly are shit at casting. I'd happily take your job.

text: I have spent several hundred hours in each installment of the Hitman series.  Some seem to be forgetting many moments in previous installments where 47 went up against an entire division of police forces (i.e. The Professional, 2007) or against a South American cartel-militia, or however many enemies came running after you pulled out your ballers and started blasting.    How many times when playing did you just say "F&@# it, I can't find the right disguise to get into the kitchen and poison the soup so I'm just gonna kill every human in front of me."  This worked, and advanced you to the next level so thusly it is arguably an acceptable route for the film to take.  In the trailer I see elements true to the series and I see a lot of pizzazz.  On the other hand, they found an actor who is both convincingly emotionally distant and intelligent.  He clearly is more naturally suited to the role than the former and has done a bit of homework with a console controller or keyboard in his hand.  Lets be real, he looks far more like the character than the porn agent from "The Girl Next Door", Timothy Olyphant.    I would like to see less action elements but this is a video game crowd you are catering to and not just Hitman fans, fans of... Transformers, Call of Duty...  Some of the action stuff was straight up cheesy but oh well, whaddaya gonna do.

text: Like Absolution, it seems that the Hitman movies have confused "Stealth" with "ACTION EXPLOSIONS! BLAM BLAM!!!"  The Hitman series is about introspection, an assassin who struggles with his own self identity and only rarely shows empathy. He's not a villain, and he's not a mindless killer either. He's a man with a job to do who can't allow himself to care for others.  A hitman movie should have a vibe that feels similar to No Country for Old Men. A slow character driven suspense thriller with some action on the side.

text: So, the point of the Hitman games is to be discreet. You're thrown into the dangerous environment with, at best, a silenced pistol, and, at worst, nothing but a fibrewire to strangle people with. You have an objective, a target, and your goal is to sneak in, neutralize your target, and escape without any security or a shred of evidence left behind. That means you'll have to sneak, find alternate ways of getting inside, knock out some troublesome guards, disguise as them, bypass security measures, get rid of evidence, all of that. As such, getting a perfect score on a level means that the police will have no leads, and, for all they know, it was a freak accident that killed the victim. That is, when they're not found dead a few hours later, when the killer is long gone.  That's the "perfect" score in a level, because this works well with Agent 47's reputation of a walking myth, an urban legend that nobody really believes. "The perfect assassin, cloned in some science facility", scoffs everyone, while 47 is right beside them, well disguised and inconspicuous.  Many people, myself included, love those games because of this mechanic. The mechanic that you have to watch your surroundings, find an appropriate way to dispose of the target, and carry it out. It's a puzzle game, of sorts, with lots of action and an interesting story to boot.  Now that I've given a quick resume of the aspects of the Hitman games, please rewatch the trailer, and you'll understand exactly why I'm not going to be watching the movie.

text: Just finished playing Hitman Absolution yesterday and was wondering: Why isn't Hitman the new James Bond in movies?  The answer is simple: Cause no actor was able to impersonate Agent 47 yet. The first actor (don't even know the name) had the physics but could not act at all. Now Orlando Bloom seems to be ideal for the acting part, but all the time I look at him I'm wondering:  Why the hell didn't he build up muscles for the movie? His shoulders look so thin!  Agent 47 is a living killer machine and not some delicate bald Legolas! I think Orlando Bloom is a good choice, cause it takes the brand Hitman to a next Level. But really? Did this guy even visit the gym before making the movie?  Also, from what I see I'm missing the black humor of the game (e.g. the sushi guy elevator scene, which was glorious) as well as the ridiculous costumes. I wish Quentin Tarantino had been director for Hitman. He knows how to portrait ridiculous characters, as well as ice-cold-killers.

text: You know what this movie lacks (despite the obvious Hitman-stealth stuff)...  *Elegance*  What I mean is, 47 should be able to walk to the end of a corridor with swat on either side dual wielding the ballers, then get headshots on both sides, like in the first movie just before he dives into the river... Then just casually walks into the tailor's with soaked clothes and no socks on, and walk out looking even better than the previous scene...  He should be able to clear out the room without any change in facial expression, shooting only the security officials, and be gone without any civilian seeing his face...  Why the hell is this dude doing a matrix bullet-time dodge?!?!?!  Look at H4BM's first mission "Death of a Showman" where he walks up to the gate, talks to the foul-mouthed idiot, them smashes the gate open with the dude's face before gracefully stepping over him like he's a chewing gum on the floor...  And how he simply watches as Alvaro D'Alvade gets shot by his acting partner for real, and then drops the chandelier on Delahunt when he rushes forward to see what's going on, all without moving from his premium spot in the audience stands.  In the first movie you see a bunch of SWAT walk in to the lift... and when the lift opens again... their all dead.. no body saw what happened.  This is not what anyone wants from the series... Just call this movie something else and we'll watch it as a movie in it's own right, instead of having our hopes for the movie crushed by it's savage murdering of the name, without even having the courtesy to cleanly use a fiber wire.

text: I'll be honest, I sincerely hope this whole "video games into movies" things doesn't become a trend. Cause if there's one thing Hollywood has proved over and over, it's that it can't do video game based movies right. There's no better way to piss off a fandom than to take their beloved characters and turn them into something they're not. If this does become a trend, hopefully developers will get more involved and do their games justice on the big screen. I'm hoping that's what's going to happen with the new Assassin's Creed movie. But it definitely isn't going to start here. This may be a great movie, but it's not Hitman

text: So for people bitching about it not being like the game. I played every hitman game and what would be the point of making a movie with total stealth and different targets for 2 whole hours. That's literally boring. And if I recall you could go in guns blazing on some missions. And dont give me thst bullshit of if you go in guns blazing you don't get the concept of the game bullshit. Case and point of changing games to movies. DOOM was a game turned into movie when they came out with DOOM 3 the game I believe back in 04. If you played DOOM it was slash up kill all demon game and trying to figure out about the company in the future UAC. When Doom 3 came out for the first time you were to save the world from hell itself. Now the movie gave a different story and said it was mutation in genes that did it. Completely changed the story from the game. Even the last Hitman movie was not like the games neither was different game movies like AC, Heavenly sword, Halo foward onto dawn. Hell Gears of War books tell a different story from the games and goes more in depth about the war itself  and  I don't see people bitching about it. Hell fast and furious went from street racing to action movie. So because it's not like the game it's going to either suck or just be a waste of time to some people. Yet this movie has not even came out yet. They can still change shit.

text: No matter what please don't make this another stupidly cliché movie! PLEASE!  I think we've all grown tired of the cliché bullet dodging, and the way the plot always goes in the main characters favor.  Example from trailer: Instead of having an ENTIRE SWAT TEAM zipline towards a guy who is proven to be a trained assassin and extremely dangerous, which will obviously lead to their deaths, why not just stop his car and snipe him from a distance? The answer is pretty simple: It will actually be able to kill him, and if it doesn't and he somehow manages to escape it wont look "badass".  What I want to see in this movie (and in all movies in general) is LOGIC and REALISM. When the main character manages to escape a situation where there is logic and realism it makes the movie/scenario much more entertaining and fun to watch.  So please, don't make me want to punch a wall out of the stupidity that's put in a scene just to provide some sort of an excuse so that the plot will be able to continue.

text: I was hoping the new Hitman movie would be a twist that the ICA thinks that the movie brought too much attention to "the real" 47 and he is contracted to kill the executives of the film. Here's a good scene: A movie exec sits a a desk on the phone talking about how the movie didn't have anything to do with the games but that it still made him money. Two gloved hands and a taunt thin wire emerge from a shadow behind him. He hangs up the phone and 47 begins to strangle him. As the shot zooms in on 47's face we see his eyes shadowed, an emotionless stern expression of only silent intent on his face. As the exec slowly loses conciseness he makes a final grasp at 47's shirt disheveling it slightly then his hand falls to the side of his chair. 47 removes the fiber wire from the exec's neck and lays it on the desk. (Jesper kyd's Apocalypse starts to play) He pauses and straightens his shirt and tie. Then picks up the fiber wire and climbs through the window. After exiting a back alley 47 disappears into a crowd.   Now that's a Hitman movie!

text: I have played all the game and I have several points (in respect, mind you) to make to a few comments I see. First off to @jesse jibran .. you say they should already know.. but the fact or point of the agency was to be a separate and discrete agency no others knew of. Agent 47 was literally known as a ghost to the communities and authorities. Second to others ignorant to the mythology.. they complain that 47 is supposed to be silent.. TECHNICALLY it's just that he CAN be silent and it's ONE of his skills he's known for and it's meant to be emphasized the most in Hitman: Silent Assassin.. although even in that game it's still an optional method as always. It all use to depend on the mission 47 was in that he would make a choice of which method he needed or preferred.You fans really need to start paying closer attention to the story details. Now if you WANT a more silent plot, that's a different story, but it seems they probably didn't go as much in that direction this time. @ROHAN ROY CHOWDHURY The first movie was not terrible as it actually stuck closer to game details, but I am glad to see another potential try at it. @Zachkills4  I do think it's interesting this movie more explains his abilities and origins unlike the first, and even goes in an enhanced scene display of those abilities, .. unrealistic, yes.. but to be fair he is enhanced .. which equals unrealistic.  Third to @SERPENTONORTHAM1992   about the whole neo comment. In the latest game.. they did start to show such related effects of him being able to do focus based skills. You could dramatically slow time as you focus on all the enemies you wanted to hit and how. You first do this near the end of the first mission after you kill Diana. He was (never meant to be neo) is debatable depending on how you see it. That is all.

text: So balls to the wall action, again... I bet he'll fall in love again, too. Here's how you make a Hitman movie; DON'T have it star 47. He's the silent killer in the background, and we follow the hero cop. We're led to believe 47's the villain, until we find out the target is a pedophilic arms dealer for international terrorists selling biological weapons. THAT'S a hitman movie. Every time the cop thinks he has him, 47 slips through, because no one knows what he really looks like and the disguises work. Have one, MAYBE two action scenes, likely at the very end, because in the games there usually is a shootout there, and the rest is a crime drama with minor sci-fi elements because he's a clone and we have a bio-weapon.

text: REVIEW: just saw the movie and I was blown away. You can say that it's a typical action movie, but it has a lot of things many action movies lack these days, such as THE ACTION!!! Nowadays it's all about long talks and many emotions, but in this movie there are so many epic sequences and there is still time for drama (well, maybe not a lot - especially one part when the female protagonist meets her father).  The story was quite exciting, reminded me a little bit of 'Wanted' (but the plot twist happens in 'Hitman' earlier), however the end was spectacular. That last scene (not counting the encore) was so thrilling and there really is a space for a sequel, but let's just see how good this one will do.

text: In the Hitman series, 47 was a Silent Assassin. No one had ever seen him, people thought he was a ghost or a myth, that he didn't exist. He always got the job done, left no witnesses, even the target never knew what hit him. 47'd make it look like an accident and would leave no evidence. He'd rarely use his silverballers, just his bare hands, fiber wire, anesthetics etc.  In the movie trailer, what I see, he goes through security wearing a long coat wielding guns and ammunition, gets caught on purpose, kicks a table, breaks the handcuffs, kills/strangles everyone and leaves the room with a disguise on. The next thing you see that he's shooting with a pair of handguns in middle of an intersection, while the whole traffic watches. A jet propeller explodes, a car explodes, a helicopter explodes and other goes straight into a building. So much for stealth and anonymity.  tl;dr : Thanks Hollywood, you've ruined our favourite assassin.

text: I guess comments will depend on what one expects when watching the movie.  Never played any Hitman games, so I can't tell if it fits or not with the guy from the videogame. From the different comments, I would gather that they messed up that part pretty hard if their goal was to follow and illustrate the franchise. I will certainly agree as well with the fact there are loaaaaaads of impossibilities in there. But again : fit/unfit depends on your expectations of the movie. I for one have had a very good time watching the movie, as it is exactly what I was expecting : action-packed movie, where I can be a brainless spectator in my sofa and enjoy a pretty show. I couldn't care less about physical/technical impossibilities. They're plenty in each and every MI's or James Bond's and I've enjoyed them all. I got my 90 min of fireworks. Happy panda ^^

text: I rate this 1/10. Features from the Hitman game series are still there such as the disguise but why do Agent 47 kill too much? Agent 47 is not a terrorist but a hired killer (or I may say stealth-using killer) please in the next part of the movie make it less attached on the killing part and make more scene of his personal life, like how he do when there is no contract for him. And also.... is he using silenced gun or non-silenced gun? Edit: In the Hitman 2: Silent Assassin, from the beginning he is a good guy but when Father Vittorio is kidnapped by the Russian Mafia he finds vengeance. But in this movie....... what is he fighting for? Agent 47 retired for good reasons and in this movie he suddenly got again in his job? I don't really understand what is really happening in the movie because all I see in the trailer is killing, assasinating, and terrorizing. You should add a methodic way of assassinating/killing a target to make the movie more exciting such as the disguise thingy, the secret passages and make some fiberwire assassination scenes sometime it would help to make the movie MOOOOOOORE thrilling and not boring to watch.

text: Personally, I liked the movie. Hold your horses before you call me an idiot in your reply. But, it is a generic shooter, a typical Michael Bay movie, as if he directed it. Guns blazing, explosions, constant action and shooting everywhere are fun, but are so constant that you know how each action scene is going to play out. 47 never misses a hit, while everyone else misses him completely.  Fun movie, but did not capture the classic Hitman feel the game has. 47 is a Silent Assassin, not someone who likes to get caught on purpose.  In conclusion: entertaining movie after a long day, when you want to see a lot of violence and action, but not a good adaptation of Hitman games at all.
